## What is a UVM Agent?

A UVM agent is the fundamental unit of reusable verification IP in UVM. It encapsulates all the verification components needed for one protocol interface:

- **Driver:** Converts sequence items (transactions) into pin-level DUT stimulus.
- **Monitor:** Observes DUT interface signals and reconstructs transactions.
- **Sequencer:** Manages flow of transactions from sequences to the driver.

A well-designed agent can be reused across multiple projects that use the same protocol, reducing verification bring-up time from weeks to days.

## Active vs Passive Agent

```systemverilog
class my_agent extends uvm_agent;
  `uvm_component_utils(my_agent)

  my_driver    drv;
  my_monitor   mon;
  my_sequencer seqr;

  function void build_phase(uvm_phase phase);
    super.build_phase(phase);
    mon = my_monitor::type_id::create("mon", this);
    if (is_active == UVM_ACTIVE) begin
      drv  = my_driver::type_id::create("drv", this);
      seqr = my_sequencer::type_id::create("seqr", this);
    end
  endfunction

  function void connect_phase(uvm_phase phase);
    if (is_active == UVM_ACTIVE)
      drv.seq_item_port.connect(seqr.seq_item_export);
  endfunction
endclass
```

| Mode | Components | Use case |
|---|---|---|
| `UVM_ACTIVE` | Driver + Monitor + Sequencer | Primary interface driving stimulus |
| `UVM_PASSIVE` | Monitor only | Snooping a bus without driving |

## The Driver: Pin-Level Stimulus Generation

The driver pulls transaction objects from the sequencer and converts them to pin-level waveforms:

```systemverilog
class my_driver extends uvm_driver #(my_txn);
  `uvm_component_utils(my_driver)

  virtual my_if vif;  // Virtual interface handle

  task run_phase(uvm_phase phase);
    forever begin
      seq_item_port.get_next_item(req);  // Get transaction
      drive_transaction(req);             // Drive pins
      seq_item_port.item_done();          // Signal completion
    end
  endtask

  task drive_transaction(my_txn txn);
    @(posedge vif.clk);
    vif.addr  <= txn.addr;
    vif.data  <= txn.data;
    vif.write <= txn.write;
    vif.valid <= 1'b1;
    @(posedge vif.clk iff vif.ready);
    vif.valid <= 1'b0;
  endtask
endclass
```

## The Monitor: Passive Observation

The monitor samples the interface and creates transactions, which it broadcasts via a TLM analysis port:

```systemverilog
class my_monitor extends uvm_monitor;
  `uvm_component_utils(my_monitor)

  uvm_analysis_port #(my_txn) ap;  // Broadcast to scoreboard, coverage
  virtual my_if vif;

  function void build_phase(uvm_phase phase);
    super.build_phase(phase);
    ap = new("ap", this);
  endfunction

  task run_phase(uvm_phase phase);
    forever begin
      my_txn txn;
      @(posedge vif.clk iff vif.valid && vif.ready);
      txn = my_txn::type_id::create("txn");
      txn.addr  = vif.addr;
      txn.data  = vif.data;
      txn.write = vif.write;
      ap.write(txn);  // Broadcast to all connected subscribers
    end
  endtask
endclass
```

## Virtual Interface Connection

The virtual interface connects the agent's class-based components to the actual DUT signals:

```systemverilog
// In top-level testbench (module, not class)
initial begin
  // Set virtual interface in config_db
  uvm_config_db #(virtual my_if)::set(
    null, "uvm_test_top.env.agent", "vif", my_vif);
end

// In agent or driver
function void build_phase(uvm_phase phase);
  if (!uvm_config_db #(virtual my_if)::get(
        this, "", "vif", vif))
    `uvm_fatal("NOVIF", "Virtual interface not found")
endfunction
```

## Agent Packaging for Reuse

A reusable agent is structured as a package:
```
my_protocol_agent/
  my_txn.sv         ← Transaction type
  my_seqr.sv        ← Sequencer (usually just typedeffed)
  my_driver.sv      ← Driver
  my_monitor.sv     ← Monitor
  my_agent.sv       ← Agent container
  my_coverage.sv    ← Optional: functional coverage
  my_sequences.sv   ← Library of reusable sequences
  my_agent_pkg.sv   ← Package that imports all above
  my_if.sv          ← Interface definition
```

> A correctly designed agent should be instantiable in any testbench with three steps: (1) import the package, (2) instantiate the interface and connect to DUT, (3) set the virtual interface in config_db. Zero other changes needed.
